# pip.conf.local.example
# Machine-specific pip overrides
#
# pip uses a layered config system (each level overrides the previous):
#   1. /etc/pip.conf          (site-wide)
#   2. ~/.config/pip/pip.conf  (user â€” managed by this dotfiles module)
#   3. $VIRTUAL_ENV/pip.conf   (per-virtualenv)
#
# Since this dotfiles module manages ~/.config/pip/pip.conf via stow,
# prefer these approaches for machine-specific settings:
#
# Option A: Environment variables (recommended for direnv/.envrc)
#   export PIP_INDEX_URL=https://pypi.corp.example.com/simple/
#   export PIP_TRUSTED_HOST=pypi.corp.example.com
#   export PIP_CERT=/path/to/corporate-ca-bundle.pem
#   export PIP_EXTRA_INDEX_URL=https://pypi.org/simple/
#
# Option B: Site-level config (/etc/pip.conf)
#   Useful for system-wide corporate mirrors on managed machines.
#   [global]
#   index-url = https://pypi.corp.example.com/simple/
#   trusted-host = pypi.corp.example.com
#   cert = /path/to/corporate-ca-bundle.pem
#
# All pip config keys can be set as env vars with the PIP_ prefix.
# See: https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/topics/configuration/
